TY  - JOUR
T1  - Citizenship and Impression Management: Good Soldiers or Good Actors?
AU  - Bolino, Mark C.
Y1  - 1999/01/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1999.1580442
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1999.1580442
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 82
EP  - 98
VL  - 24
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Previous research on organizational citizenship behavior suggests that employees who engage in such behavior are ?good soldiers,? acting selflessly on behalf of their organizations. However, such behaviors also may be impression enhancing and self-serving. In this article 1 provide a framework showing how impression-management concerns may motivate citizenship behavior and address the consequences of citizenship in this context, as well as the interaction of impression-management motives with motives identified in previous research on citizenship. Finally, I discuss the methodological issues associated with isolating self-serving from other-serving motivation and implications for future theory development.
AB  - Previous research on organizational citizenship behavior suggests that employees who engage in such behavior are ?good soldiers,? acting selflessly on behalf of their organizations. However, such behaviors also may be impression enhancing and self-serving. In this article 1 provide a framework showing how impression-management concerns may motivate citizenship behavior and address the consequences of citizenship in this context, as well as the interaction of impression-management motives with motives identified in previous research on citizenship. Finally, I discuss the methodological issues associated with isolating self-serving from other-serving motivation and implications for future theory development.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1999.1580442
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1999.1580442
Y2  - 2026/04/24
