TY  - JOUR
T1  - Specialists, Generalists, and Polymorphs: Spatial Advantages of Multiunit Organization in a Single Industry
AU  - Usher, John M.
Y1  - 1999/01/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1999.1580446
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1999.1580446
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 143
EP  - 150
VL  - 24
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - I critique and extend niche width theory to provide an explanatory framework for the success of multiunit firms in single industries. A greater emphasis on spatial variation in organizational environments allows the fitness strategy of polymorphism to be developed more adequately and multiunit expressions of the specialist and generalist strategies to be added to the theory. I develop a set of testable propositions regarding the specific environmental conditions for the success of each strategy and consider research and managerial implications.
AB  - I critique and extend niche width theory to provide an explanatory framework for the success of multiunit firms in single industries. A greater emphasis on spatial variation in organizational environments allows the fitness strategy of polymorphism to be developed more adequately and multiunit expressions of the specialist and generalist strategies to be added to the theory. I develop a set of testable propositions regarding the specific environmental conditions for the success of each strategy and consider research and managerial implications.
